{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4f5d55cc-dba1-4542-bf42-83836e09abb7","content":"## What happened\n\nC# 14 adds **first-class Span support** with implicit array → `ReadOnlySpan<T>` conversions. This changes overload resolution: `array.Contains(num)` now binds to:\n\n```\nMemoryExtensions.Contains<int>(ReadOnlySpan<int>, int)   // ← new winner\n```\n\ninstead of the .NET 9 resolution:\n\n```\nEnumerable.Contains<int>(IEnumerable<int>, int)           // ← old winner\n```\n\n`ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a **ref struct** — it can't be boxed or passed through the reflection-based interpreter that `Compile(preferInterpretation: true)` uses, so you get a runtime failure.\n\n## Fix\n\nDisambiguate so the compiler picks the `Enumerable` overload. Either option works:\n\n**Option A — Explicit static call:**\n```csharp\nusing System.Linq;\n\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\n**Option B — Cast to `IEnumerable<int>`:**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n```\n\nBoth force the compiler back to the non-span `Enumerable.Contains` overload, which the expression-tree interpreter can handle.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8d35e9ac-869f-4fa5-9053-a7031cae51c9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 that affects LINQ expression trees calling `.Contains()` on `int[]` arrays.\n\nLet me think about what changed in .NET 10 / C# 14 that would cause this.\n\nIn C# 14 / .NET 10, there's a significant change related to extension members. C# 14 introduces **extension types** (formerly \"roles and extensions\"), but more relevantly, there's a change in how the compiler resolves `Contains` on arrays.\n\nActually, let me think more carefully. The issue is likely related to the fact that in .NET 10, `System.Array` or `Span<T>` now implements `IEnumerable<T>` differently, or the